title: Grateful Dead Live at Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum on 1993-02-21
lineage: Unknown Mics (FOB) > DAT (48khz) > Tascam DA-20mkII > Hosa S/PDIF > Delta DiO 2496 > Peak > downsampled to 44.1k/normalized to 98% > SHN (no DAE)
description: Bertha-> Greatest Story Ever Told, Lazy River Road, Eternity, Ramble On Rose, Queen Jane Approximately, Row Jimmy, Promised Land Liberty, Corinna-> Crazy Fingers-> Estimated Prophet-> Samson & Delilah, Drums-> Jam-> The Wheel-> I Need A Miracle-> Morning Dew, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text: it made it this show did not originally get posted and I was worried that it was not circulating.  As I was seeing nineties Dead, many would say that it was not worth going to their shows, so when I made it to Oakland and got treated to NEW SONGS, my well seasoned ears almost fell off.  Needless to say, they were still creative till the end.  Thanks to all who make the Archive possible.  It is GREAT !
Liberty LSD made me think the liberty was "deep Elem".First Liberty

Nice friendly show. First off, Thank You Archive.
I have been able to get Every Single Show I attended - save one encore - from you guys.

Now to the review.
I've had the second set of this on tape for a few years now and it was instantly one of my favorites. I've nearly wore it out and am a little afraid to play it.

I havn't dl this one yet but will.
Great show... nice one to put on when you have guests or friends over and need a easy to hear show. No big crazyness just nice clean Grateful Dead.

sweet i'm not really into 90s dead, but i really dig this show. the crowd noise is a lot of fun, you can hear a very happy sounding lady say that greatest story ever told is "one of my favorite songs!"
honestly not a vg show VG fob recording, but, really, a sloppy and odd show. A few intermittent bits of good stuff, but otherwise pretty messy and weak.

First 'Acoustic' sound This was the first show where Jerry played the acoustic midi for a lot of songs..took a couple songs to adjust..the sound would stay for many shows in the year...fucking beautiful Liberty, the first and very much the best one..i'll never forget this show, had a lot of fun...5 stars for Liberty and the other breakouts as well the acoustic direction
Somebody has to have the SBD!!! I'd nominate this show for a Dick's Picks if I could. Highly underrated show. The other (new) aud source is better than this one IMO. Small blessings and whatnot.

- Wel,, I haven't really listened to this recording, but the show was amazing, and archive can't find the item enough for me to review the other recording. 

Wow! A real hidden gem. Goes right up there with Irvine Meadows '87 as one of my favorite shows ever. Three brand new songs, all played well, and the rest of the show played like Gods, the whole band, especially Garcia. Not a sign of the later decay. Like a breath of spring.

My Favorite Show Ever I'm biased because I was at this show, but this is the one I have listened to, and shared this show more than any other. There was, for lack of a better term, a sense of reverence in the room that night. During Jerry's solo in Crazy Fingers, the audience was so quiet you could have heard a pin drop. That solo is my favorite guitar solo of all time, and this performance is what turned Crazy Fingers into my favorite Grateful Dead song. Absolutely sublime. Oh, and also, we were told by an eye witness that we met in line the next night, that both Bill Clinton and Al Gore were backstage that night.

great show! check the sndbrd version of it. So clean! I was there for this show and had a straight line of sight to Jerry. In a chair, 1st row, Jerry side w/ my buddies.(1st row of seats on Jerry side by main aisle that weren't floor.) great sound, acousticy -  Maybe a Dave's picks or official release to come!? So glad I made it to this show, on the drive from Humboldt stopped along the way to enjoy Humboldt brewery. Such fond memories- Miss U Jerry!
